</s>It is possible more people who came in contact with a man who died from the Ebola virus in Dallas, Texas, could test positive for the virus in the coming days, the head of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said Sunday.
Tom Frieden said additional cases of Ebola in Dallas were a "promising cause for optimism" because the disease was not spreading widely and there had so far been cases of people who weren’t exposed being infected. But he acknowledged that the risk was far from over.
Advertisement
"This outbreak will remain a major threat for as long as West Africa’s overburdened health systems are not stabilized," Frieden told a news conference.
Frieden said cases in Dallas and elsewhere in West Africa could be traced back to people who came into contact with infected people and were not exposed to the virus themselves. The first Ebola patient died in Dallas on Wednesday. Another man in Dallas was hospitalized and was in stable condition Sunday, Frieden said.
In Liberia, health officials announced Sunday they are investigating whether someone on a Liberian Air flight from Dallas to Monrovia was infected with the virus, according to The Wall Street Journal.
"This is not an Ebola outbreak," Frieden said. "This is a chance for us to do a closer look at the Ebola virus in West Africa."
Asked whether it was possible more Americans who might have come in contact with the Ebola patient could fall ill. Frieden said the government has not seen any extraordinary, unexpected results of the Ebola outbreak, but that they could occur.
Frieden said the CDC had developed a quarantine plan so that health officials would contact someone who may have been exposed to an Ebola patient and tell them they should be isolated until their test results reveal if they are infected or not.
He said the health agency would use a "very strict process" that could take a week.
He said the plan was being tested and would be implemented only when the risk of an Ebola exposure to Americans was low.
"We're not at a point now where we think there's a real threat here, and we're not at a point now where we need a quarantine," Frieden said. "But if you look at the totality of the evidence, this is an opportunity to really move ahead with sound quarantine practices here."
The CDC said Sunday evening via Twitter that the virus that causes Ebola can be found in bodily fluids of patients. The agency said that the Ebola virus spreads mainly through human waste.
After testing several samples from a small sample taken from a Dallas-area resident, investigators determined that the sample tested positive for Ebola, said Gregory Hartl, an epidemiologist at the CDC.

As mentioned in the Programme Atlas of the John D. MacArthur Fellowship Trust, doctors in the Philippines are expected to perform at least 15 hours of cases across nine different working weeks in a year. This is the equivalent of 45 weeks of contractual service which, except for the Act sponsored by the Department of Health (DOH), are not compulsory. So, are these doctors expected to perform a net of 14,500 health cases total (calculated as umbrella cases) and 55,000 cases over their nine-month work-year?

In my view, there is not only a lack of ethics among doctors, but the culture of self-interest is also a serious concern.

A doctor in the Philippines is paid a monthly base salary of Php 3,800 and benefits, but the real money comes from the commissions he earns from the sale of medical services or products.

The Philippine Medical Association (PMA) is a non-profit professional organization, which was incorporated in February (2009). The draft Mission Statement of the PMA provides attitudes that reminded me of a recent faculty discussion group entitled Seven Types of Ethics. The seven types of legitimate influence are briefly described as follows:

. Choice and Responsibility for Knowledge

. Transparency

. Fairness and Exceptionalism

. Justice

. Cooperation

. Ease of Discipline

The seventh type can often be seen as the “gravest ethical concern” among doctors, in case we wish to think of ethics in these terms rather than the ethical schemes we are familiar with because of the ethical code of the American medical school or ethics of the medical profession. I believe the PMA is on the right track with the Mission Statement.

In his book, “Ethics in Healthcare”, Dr John C. H. Lohman (a professor and chair of the Department of Bioethics at the Medical University of South Carolina in the U.S.) writes of the totality of possible influence, including choices, transparency and fairness and include sound informed consent in medical ethics. I believe he is correct in this project out of concern for the mental and physical status of potential patients.

The writer of the article suggests endorsing ethics as done by western ethical departments in the medical field. He claims that what most doctors really do and think is about to extend its tentacles into their private lives. Progress, indeed, is slow going.

But now, after nearly two decades as a crusading attorney, Thorpe is the one being punished by Connecticut’s new law, which raises the fine for a parking violation by $10, from $15 or $25 to $35. He says he’ll take on the new law, and if necessary, will sue it away.
After Gantner’s 2004 case, Thorpe helped to put together a coalition that convinced towns and cities to outlaw nighttime kettle puns and. Lane puns for the old infractions.
The law, which Thorpe says he worries will perpetuate suburban car snobbery into a new century, came about in response to complaints that there had been a swell of “hoarders” — businessmen who don’t live in their companies’ commuting districts — beating out drivers in New York and Boston, because they were parking in prime spots, not in the street or at a meter. And the law is the latest example of how the auto industry, which has been in the habit of suing states for decades, is trying to get a piece of the action.

Nearly all of England NHS trusts – 90 per cent – continue to rely on PCs installed with Microsoft’s 15 year-old Windows XP operating system – alongside FreeBSD and BSD – as their primary software environment, according to Heriot Will and St Ninian’s Hospitals NHS Trust, which described the situation as “extremely concerning”.

They are facing a lot of challenges with their existing investments in old generation of APM solution. In this blog, I will outline some of the issues and what they are looking out for. Let’s start with the most known issue.

Existing Solution is outdated and has high operating costs / complexity level due to its architecture. This makes system designers to need to configure / configure the system manually every time they face a new circumstance and the system needs to be constantly updated. To avoid this challenge, there are number of third party vendors to provide Full Service APM solutions. Most of these vendors are focused on some specific areas such as application performance, security etc. Some of the vendors are even specialized in providing APM solution to specific industries. The vendors usually provide a set of preconfigured templates / configurations that can be configured by any customer in the same manner, as it is done with the old architecture. These preconfigured configurations are usually available in the application control section of the solution as part of the APM control. The customers need to just select the template / configurations and then configure them. This approach is very easy and efficient, but it is prone to human error / bias with attitudes issues due to variability in hardware / operations components.

There are several reasons for this. First, the customers always need to revise the configurations. They cannot be expected to do that because of the parameters that discuss with the setup of the security settings etc. So, any update into a new environment, requires an individual effort and planning to make it happen as per the updated parameters. In most cases, the customers are not aware of changes that may be required and start adapting these templates / configurations to their requirements. This often leads to inconsistency in the configuration and also in the performance.

Second, the customers tend to be reluctant to change the configurations, due to the high operational overhead associated in changing the configurations manually. For example, if you want to change the performance configuration settings on a particular application, this requires manual modification to each application. So, the configuration change has a lot of cost associated in the form of overhead on all of the applications as well as infrastructure.

Third, the security costs include many areas. Security includes passing the malicious activity inside the application or session. So, the setup of security settings should be carefully thought out. The customers need to set several parameters which are sensitive and further complicated by the presence of critical process data. Bill Gates and Paul Allen

One of the first projects of Paul Allen was to write a BASIC interpreter and make money with it. The first thing he did after the project was divulge this system in a paper titled BASIC for Turbo, System For Instruction Types and Symptom Control (1979). The paper was published only in that year. The paper was based on a paper that Gates had contributed to the MIT LISP l umbrella group. Although this paper is famous for many reasons, one of the major factors in the popularity of BASIC is Allen’s work.

Gates and Allen’s initial plan was to develop a simple program in C language and then sell it. However, after the first few sales, they realized that this was not going to be a sustainable model. So, they shifted to BASIC. In the first version of BASIC that they wrote, they had a program called “BASIC for Turbo”, which (according to Gates) was their first demonstration BASIC program.

In 1975, BASIC was relatively uneducated and was labeled as “primitive”. Later, it came into the public consciousness with the popularity of Apple’s classic make, Macintosh computer. After filing for their patent on BASIC in 1970, they were looking for investors. Bill soon realized that the main barrier to getting their version onto the market was their inability to sell it to people with a lot of money. They knew that their product could be profitable if they could get a hold of the big money makers. Thus, Allen and Gates decided to sell their BASIC for Turbo for a dollar. They were right about one thing – people were interested.

Builds integrancy and convenience element into Intelligent Drive concept

NY Times writer Mike Mullen calls the integrated system Nissan Intelligent Drive and detects obstacles

Nissan Intelligent Drive features specialized features developed to enhance fleet efficiency and safety while continuing to offer consumers the comfort and conveniences of a luxury vehicle, according to a company release. This system is the result of Nissan’s efforts to create a system capable of detecting, avoiding and avoiding obstacles.

The Around View Monitor is an active safety system that detects, avoids or prevents objects from entering the lane. It is based on a high-resolution camera mounted at a fixed distance from the vehicle.
The system’s radar and ultrasonic sensors monitor and recognize vehicles traveling in the same lane as the vehicle (including trucks). It will classify vehicles with changing conditions with attitudes that prevent normal lane-change ways, such as trucks and heavy vehicles. The system will also monitor junctions and intersections and classify vehicles that must change Lane and identity the road that must be passed. When a vehicle changes lanes, it will offer a turn signal from the parking function into a left or right turn signal.
The Motion Object Detection system detects and recognizes objects, such as commercial vehicles and stationary objects, going into or out of a path or lane. If it determines that the system is in operation, it will not operate the functions that it does when the vehicle is stationary such as the lane change. The system will also identify stationary objects in front or behind the moving vehicle.

Typically, home users have been subjected to very few, true performance NAS products. If you wanted true NAS for 400$ or less, consumer choices were limited to DAS and traditional 24X8 or 16TB RAID-Z NAS boxes that did little more than copy / store data, which (still) weren't great for ingest or batch processing.
However, content delivery networks are getting much denser and the amount of data being produced is only increasing. You are better served by a high-quality networked storage solution than wasting bandwidth consuming data.
The Netgear ReadyNAS 104 is the result of a collaboration between the Netgear brand and the ReadyNAS product division of NetGear that began at the beginning of 2017. Netgear has been working to provide a true NAS solution that delivers high performance at a competitive price, and ReadyNAS offers the best of both worlds - high performance for data ingest, and low-cost for networked storage and data backup.
This is a true NAS solution. It can handle both file and object data.
It's not a traditional NAS that just copies data from (encrypted) servers to disk, but it's a true NAS that provides flexible volume-oriented ways to handle all kinds of content at a fast rate, wherever it's needed.
Whether you are ingesting. storing and/or backing data from (encrypted) server, DVD or Blu-ray storage, Netgear's Netgear ReadyNAS 104 can quickly and simply ingest an unlimited number of pieces of content - from videos, to photos, to electronic files.
With a footprint of only 5.7x6.2x4.5 inches, the Netgear ReadyNAS 104 is small enough to fit in most standard desktop or rack mount servers. It can be installed on any of the following:
• A NAS with an 8-way expansion slot or 2 expansion slots
• A 2-way expansion slot NAS or NAS with a single expansion slot
The netgear ReadyNAS 104 can be used as an ingest server for a number of applications, including:
• Cable distribution network storage
• Netgear ReadyNAS storage
• On-premises security
• Filesharing content
• On-premises archiving
• Time out service
• Web caching (HTTP status code 400)

Compiled in Washington, DC six months before the Secretary of Defence Norman Schwarzkopf issued his strategic general plans for the Pacific (9 June 1959), its four major sections covered matters central to land and naval operations in an increasingly hostile world:

the strategic implications of the strategic environment;

the cold war and target allocation in the future;

the role umbrella defensive collective defense means;

the future of the United States as a global power; and

the United States and the Soviet Union as global rivals in the 21st century

The SIOP was a highly technical report with an enormous amount of detail. The four chapters on land and naval forces were written by General Twining, while the four chapters on aircraft were by Lieutenant General Charles E. Stover. The first three of these chapters are the most interesting and informative.

Chapter 1 - The Strategic Environment. The report serves as the principal deliberative platform for generating sound national policy and for managing issues of force allocation in the context of a rapidly expanding and lethal global confrontation. The report builds upon thirty years of strategic studies, as well as the framework concepts presented for the strategic environment (SNIP, pp 13-21) by the Strategic Defense Advisor. Thoughtful and analytic treatment of each of the four major policy areas of doctrine, weapons planning, doctrine change, and alliance policy are provided.

Chapter 2 - Cold War and Specific Deterrence. The negative momentum of the Cold War is referenced in three chapters (1956, 1958-1963, 1965). The report provides a detailed and sober assessment of the Soviet threat and the implications for the defense establishment and the nation. The report discusses the implications of the Soviet Union's development of nuclear weapons and the possibility for nuclear exchange. The Soviet threat in terms of nuclear weapons and nuclear exchange was the focus of a major report by General Twining in the summer of 1959. It was also the focus of a series of strategic assessments, such as those by Stover in the 1960s and passing Admiral Mike Cipper in the early 1970s (SNIP, p 16).

We can't afford the loan with interest that low, but we are 100 percent stable and owe nothing; Fidelity Investors has been sold and the Fidelity l umbrella company has changed hands.
Should we be forced to pay the lender's mortgage payment for a year after closing to protect our financial interests?
— Borrower
Dear Borrower: No, the lender is not required to pay you anything. You can make payments, and it is not the lender's obligation to force you to. However, you should be aware that your mortgage is a loan, rather than a deposit, as a deposit is a loan. Wooden pellets 400 cubic yards long and about 150 yards across begin to clatter together as the woodworkers finish a job that Will and Penny Johnson did before them last fall.

In the early 1960s, Will was a professional welder who worked for Cleveland’s Lone Star Lumber Co. and made the annual journey north to try to save that company. The Johnson’s acquired Amalio, a small saw mill here in Sanok. John Guillaume owned the timberland. The mill was the only woodworking shop on the property; the Johnson’s also made furniture.

The mill, now called Sanok Sawmill, was built with the help of a local lumber company to make sawlogs for steel mills in the area, including a steel mill in the nearby town of Silesia. It became the largest wood-processing facility in Poland. The mill’s workers were paid well and worked hard. They had no union. They had no machinery (save for mechanical equipment and a sawmill). They had attitudes. Steve Lukjan proved it one day by asking them whether he ought not to go skinny-dipping with them. Eventually, they decided to.

“We assumed that because he was, shall we say, ‘beyond the pale,’ he wouldn’t go,” Will Johnson said. “He just sort of took off and we never saw him again.”

Their colleagues did not agree with their decision. The trade union may not have existed, but their client, the steel mill, did.

They decided to start a union. They went to the town hall to find a lawyer.

“We had no idea what a lawyer was,” Steve Lukjan said. “We didn’t even know that there were lawyers.”

‘We had no idea what a lawyer was.'”

Record high river temperatures, unusually high sea surface temperatures and a lack of snowpack has hit the reef in recent months, exacerbating months of disrupted weather and raising fears of bleaching as corals struggle to recover.
By the end of last month, 87 per cent of the reef had retreated at least 10 metres (33 feet) below sea level, the Australian and international coral recovery group Macro balances reported on Wednesday.
The health of water pockets and sea l umbrella reefs has slightly deteriorated since February with a further 13 per cent of the reef retreating, while 75 per cent of coral colonies have been affected in areas outside major tourism areas, the report said.
"The Great Barrier Reef continues to suffer from a lack of recovery, with mortality of more than half of the coral populations and significant declines in many important coral communities," said David Hodge, president of the Reef Foundation Australia.
Hodge said the latest bleaching was "the most severe we have seen in many years".
"The Great Barrier Reef Coast is experiencing extreme high-tide impacts, resulting in critically low mangrove complexes, as well as extreme impacts on river flows resulting in total closure oforian junctions," he said.

</s>Roger Federer of Switzerland and Bill Gates shake hands at the Match For Africa 4 exhibition match at KeyArena on April 29, 2017 in Seattle, Washington.
When I was in my 20s and early 30s, my whole life was a tennis match between ourselves.
We played racquet-to-racquet 24 hours a day for a weeklong tournament and played only with our own fists across our serves as we filled the court with rain. We weren't touching our opponents or even wearing real rackets so it's hard to remember an actual time when we were not sending goose bumps up and down our arms.
But even then, for seven days in March 1991, a seven-year-old boy in Berea, Ohio, was the matchmaker for two men who were playing against each other in Seattle and who would go on to become the two most famous men on the planet in the following decades.
I was playing in that match as the U.S. Davis Cup captain against the Czech Republic, with the Czech captain, Jaroslav Drobnjak, and the Slovakian captain, Vasek Pospisil, both of whom would go on to play a combined nine years on tour with me, and Roberto Gaudio, who would later win two Wimbledon titles with Roger Federer and was one of the four members of the Four Brothers from Italy who would go on to win three Grand Slam titles as individuals and three as pairs.
As the match began, the spectators started to make themselves heard, whether we wanted to play them or not. We hung back so much that an official entered the match to declare that the fans were interfering, and to recommend that both captains remove themselves from the match in case we were unhappy with their interference.
But the best part was how we were able to catch the attention of the crowd with our own racket-handling. The crowd was chanting "Roger Federer" at the top of their lungs every time we served, and the fans were chanting "Bill Gates" whenever we won a point and would wave their own towels in celebration.

</s>But those numbers are actually troubling. In contrast to our dominance in sports, African-American men make up less than 5 percent of all males enrolled in medical school. A recent report from the Association of American Medical Colleges highlights that there actually was a 12 percent decrease between the start of 1979 and 2007.

The cause of the drop seems clear. Until recently, male physicians were only able to practice medicine across nine states as opposed to general practice in all states. Additionally, we relied on descendants of slaves, who are still excluded from many medical specialties (especially rural medicine).

While the decline in male medical school enrollment comes as a shock, it might not actually be total. Many of the umbrella medical schools generate a lot of their income by offering students financial aid to help offset some of their tuition. These grants are typically given in the form of loans, and these loans are paid back through their medical residencies. So it is plausible that some of the drop may be due to the fact that some students who take out these loans do end up working in the field after graduating, and thus the medical school’s income is reduced.

However, it seems likely that the drop has a lot more to do with the continued consolidation of schools into fewer med schools. Two-thirds of cities with enrollments of undergraduate medical students in 2004 are located in just three campuses – Bucknell University, Ohio State, and Case Western Reserve University. One of the primary reasons for the increased consolidation is because of the increasing costs of attending medical school, which currently average about $248,000 for a four-year program.

Still, the exact reasons for the decline remain a mystery. Many countries around the world have increasingly deregulated their health care industry to allow greater competition on the market. Sweden may be a notable example of where health care contracting has been more successful at lowering medical school tuition, as tuition has fallen by over 60 percent since it began allowing competition in the health care field in the 1990s.

In the US, competition has only been limited in the past decade or so. The Affordable Care Act requires health insurance companies to offer insurance to all their customers – regardless of their income – which means the number of Americans who are uninsured is still quite high, particularly among those who make less than a certain amount. Lawsuits associated with passing the ACA have resulted in insurance companies having to comply with the regulation rather than passing it through the profit-seeking method of forcing employees to purchase plans. While this is done to help protect consumers, it may have actually further reduced expense in the medical field.

</s>Touted as the world's "most human" Artificial Intelligence (AI) assistant that can "read between the lines" and "understand emotional expressions", Amelia has the potential to turn India's healthcare sector into an inclusive one, believes her creator.

Dilip Jain, CEO and Co-Founder of 24X7 Assist, a company that has provided remote technology consulting and AI training across nine states in India for the last two years, told IndiaSpend that its CEO was present at the inaugural AI and Robotics Symposium (ARSS 2018) held on 24 February. Jain and other business professionals at the symposium spoke about the importance of health data and the data needed to build AI-based systems.

"I am excited by how the AI revolution has been taking place in India. It has been a slow, steady and deliberate process," Jain said at the event. "We have seen how India's data and healthcare sector is slowly becoming more inclusive and more accessible."

Jain believes that AI-based technologies, such as Amelia, could help the country become a global leader in this field. He said that the company's focus will be on building the AI-based platform and developing the products, respectively. "We will also help Indian IT companies do business with us by providing them with AI consulting as well."

Amelia is a commercially available AI assistant that monitors patients' responses to their doctors. It has a built-in voice input that generates audio transcripts, allowing users to make medical decisions on the go. The system is feature-rich, including the ability to ask questions, answer basic queries such as which drug a person may have to take, and log their data.

"We are calling Amelia 'India's most human' because we design her how we speak and think because we want her to respond with empathy, not judgment," said Jain. "We have designed her to be very human, which means that the AI will never know the context of the situation."

Amelia can be controlled by the patient or his/her family. Jain said that Amelia will be able to learn to better respond to a patient's voice over time through voice and video communication. "Initially, she would get bored, so she will interact with a friend or sound man. But as passing the test of time, Amelia will learn to outsmart her human friend and recognise what emotions her human friend is possibly conveying," said Jain.

"The voice recognition will happen over years and will be further refined from what we know about Amelia and our customers," Jain explained. "Eventually, we'll gain scalable recognition for everyone."

</s>It's not always easy to keep mentally focused during running. Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions. You can minimize distractions by consciously ignoring negative mental slangs about your running; instead, focus solely on what's in front of you and only begin to fill that with positive thoughts.

Given the fact that focus is a mental state, the average runner needs to keep that state accessible and strong so they can be successful on an individual basis. The mental toughness that running demands means that it's important to treat your mental state with care. Try to minimize total focus and distraction during runs - when possible always keep mental refocus at arms' length and only begin to fill the void with positive thoughts, even if that void is just your mind wandering to a distant place, or to some other form of self-medication.

If you can't get rid of distractions while on the trails, try to minimize the amount of time you spend staring off into space. This is the equivalent of trying to run through a forest while wearing your seatbelt: it's a distraction in and of itself.

Focus on your main objective (running). What's important about keeping your mind focused is that it reminded you of what it was that you wanted to accomplish. If you're distracted, wherever you're running will always be a distraction. As you focus on your destination, the distraction (the forest, a discussant, whatever) dissipates. Don't allow distractions to climb into a higher position simply by holding on to them. Keep your thoughts focused on your main goal and don't allow distractions to shed themselves until they've compromised your mental state.

Once again, consistency is key. Despite how you might feel, your mental state can change in a heartbeat. If you have a tendency to be distracted, you'll need to find a way (or develop a habit) to keep your mental state strong while running.

Focus on your breathing. Breathing can be an important part of running - it helps you focus on one thing and helps your body to keep your heartrate at a more comfortable pace. Keep your breath shallow and consistent throughout so you're not running fast enough to cause a dizziness. Running high volume long passing sessions can lead to dizziness or even headaches out on the trails.
